Add an instruction as well on how to copy /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf to local

Here is the updated code. 

Note that I used the `ssh ... sudo cat ... > file` method instead of `scp`. This is generally the best approach for Kubernetes because `/etc/kubernetes/admin.conf` is usually owned by `root` with `600` permissions. Standard `scp` would fail for a non-root user, but this method seamlessly bypasses the issue using `sudo`.

```rust
    println!("\n  Using {primary_label} IP:");
    println!("    ssh -i {ssh_priv_path} {ssh_user}@{primary_ip_to_show} \\");
    println!("      sudo kubectl --kubeconfig /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf get po -A -o wide");

    println!("\n  Using {alt_label} IP:");
    println!("    ssh -i {ssh_priv_path} {ssh_user}@{alt_ip_to_show} \\");
    println!("      sudo kubectl --kubeconfig /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf get po -A -o wide");

    println!("\n  To copy the kubeconfig to your local machine:");
    println!("    ssh -i {ssh_priv_path} {ssh_user}@{primary_ip_to_show} \\");
    println!("      sudo cat /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf > kubeconfig.yaml");

    println!("\n  To use it locally:");
    println!("    export KUBECONFIG=$PWD/kubeconfig.yaml");
    println!("    kubectl get po -A -o wide");

    Ok(())
```
